  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT332-kilavi">varaiyātu vantoḻukāniṉṟa kālattuk kiḻavaṉ kēṭpak kiḻattikkut tōḻi
          kūṟiyatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Spoken by the confidante to HER for HIM to hear in a
          time that was ccoming [and] passing by without marrying. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT332">
          <l> vanta vāṭaic cilpeyaṟ kaṭainā</l>
          <l> ṇōynīn tarumpaṭar tīra nīnayantu</l>
          <l> kūṟi ṉevaṉō tōḻi nāṟuyir</l>
          <l> maṭappiṭi taḻīit taṭakkai yāṉai</l>
          <l> kuṉṟac ciṟukuṭi yiḻitaru</l>
          <l> maṉṟa naṇṇiya malaikiḻa vōṟkē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>What if you spoke, friend,</l>
          <l rend="indent">longing to end the affliction, difficult to overcome, [and] the pain,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">on the last day of few rain, with the north wind that came,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">– to the master of the mountain, situated by the village common, <note place="foot"> The syntax of <term xml:lang="ta"> naṇṇiya </term> is well attested by many parallels, but what is this supposed to mean, a mountain situated on the village common? Irony? T.V.G. explains the small villages (<term xml:lang="ta"> ciṟukuṭi</term>) to be situated in the mountains, and the elephant pair to roam about on the village common, but that does not make the word order any more plausible. </note> </l>
          <l rend="indent2">where the broad-trunked elephant,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">having embraced the youthful female with fragrant breath, <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> nāṟu uyir </term>: "breath" is the proposal of Cām., and otherwise it is difficult to make sense of it at all.</note></l>
          <l rend="indent2">descends upon the little homes on the hills?</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
